:::summary
The government of the United States is a constitutional federal republic whose design drew self-consciously on a vast inheritance from ancient Greece and Rome, English common law, Christian natural law theory, and Enlightenment political philosophy. The Founders were steeped in classical learning — they read Cicero, Polybius, Plutarch, Aristotle, and Thucydides — and they deliberately structured the new republic to embody the classical insights about mixed government, the separation of powers, and the rule of law while grounding its moral foundations in the Christian conviction that rights are "endowed by their Creator." Understanding American government requires understanding this classical and Christian inheritance.
:::

